== Introduction to quality control with `fastQC` and `multiQC` <introduction-to-quality-control-with-fastqc-and-multiqc>

#link("https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/fastqc/")[FastQC] and #link("https://seqera.io/multiqc/")[MultiQC] are the industry-standard tools for assessing and visualising the quality of raw high-throughput sequencing (NGS) data (e.g., FASTQ, BAM, or SAM files). FastQC generates detailed QC reports for individual files, while MultiQC aggregates these metrics into a single, interactive, and comprehensive dashboard.

Here is an overview of how these tools work together and what to look for in your analysis:
= 1. The Core Tool: FastQC <id-1-the-core-tool-fastqc>

FastQC evaluates raw sequence data across ten distinct modules, providing a quick assessment *(Pass/Warning/Fail)* for metrics such as:

- _Per Base Sequence Quality_: Checks if the sequencing quality scores (Phred scores) remain high across the entire length of the read.
- _Sequence Duplication Levels_: Helps identify potential PCR over-amplification or low-complexity libraries.
- _Adapter Content_: Alerts you if raw sequencing adapters have not been fully trimmed from the ends of the reads.

== Basic Usage <basic-usage>

To run FastQC on a single or multiple FASTQ files, use the following terminal command:

```bash
fastqc read1_R1.fq.qz read1_R2.fq.qz
```

#tipBlock[
You can use `fastqc *.fq.gz` to process every file in your directory automatically or you can use loops to iterate into each file and process all fastq files with the extension `.fq.gz`.
]

```bash
for i in sample /path/to/fastq/reads/ ; do fastqc '$i' -o /path/to/fastqc/output;
done
```

