= Bonus <bonus>

Key Metrics to Monitor When reviewing your MultiQC report, pay close attention to these common warning signs:
- \*Sequence Length Distribution\*: If reads vary heavily in length, you may need to trim low-quality sequences or adapter fragments using a tool like \[Trim Galore\](https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/trim\_galore/) or \[fastp\](https://github.com/opengene/fastp).

- _Per Sequence Quality Scores_: A significant drop in quality toward the 3' end of the reads is common in Illumina sequencing. If the average score drops below 20 (indicating a 1% probability of an incorrect base call), trimming is necessary.
- _Overrepresented Sequences_: This usually indicates either adapter dimers or highly abundant transcripts (e.g., ribosomal RNA in RNA-Seq).

Additional parameters should be taken into account depending on the type of genomic data you are dealing with.
